                        =============================
                        What is Dependency Injection
                        =============================

=> The process of injecting one class object into another class is called as "Dependency Injection".
=>We can perform dependency injection in 3 ways->

      1.Setter Injection(SI)
      2.Constructor Injection(CI)
      3.Field Injection(FI)

                                1.Setter Injection
                                ===================

=> Setter injection means , injecting dependent object int target object using target class setter method.


Below is the example:
--------------------

========
Car.java
========

package ashokit.in;
public class Car {

	//we have declared a variable 
	
	private IEngine eng;
	
	//setter injection
	
	public void setEng(IEngine eng) {
		
		this.eng = eng;
	}
	public void drive() {
		
		int start =  eng.start();
		
		if(start>=1) {
			
			System.out.println("Journey started");
		}else {
			
			System.out.println("Engine is in trouble ");
		}
	}
}

Note: In the above program, 'Car' class is dependent on 'Engine' class object should be injected into 'Car' class.

Finally--> Car is dependent on engine.

=========
Main.java
=========

package ashokit.in;
public class Main {

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		//creating target object
		Car car = new Car();
		//injecting dependent object into target through setter method 
		car.setEng(new DieselEngine());
		car.drive();
	}
}
                                    
                                    2.Constructor Injection
                                    =======================

==> Constructor Injection means, injecting dependent object into target object using target class constructor.
========
car.java
========

package ashokit.in;

public class Car {

	// we have declared a variable

	private IEngine eng;
public Car(IEngine eng) {
	  
	  this.eng=eng; }
	  
	 
	public void drive() {

		int start = eng.start();

		if (start >= 1) {

			System.out.println("Journey started");
		} else {

			System.out.println("Engine is in trouble ");
		}
	}
}

=========
Main.java
=========

package ashokit.in;
public class Main {

	public static void main(String[] args) {

		  Car car = new Car(new DieselEngine()); 
		  car.drive(); 

	}
}

Q. Can we perform both SI and CI for single variable ?

Answer: Yes, we can but setter injection will override Constructor injection value .



                                      ===================
                                      Field Injection(FI)
                                      ===================
=> Field Injection(FI) means, injecting depending object into target class using target class variable is called Field Injection(FI).


We use  " REFLECTION API " to achive Field Injection(FI).


Let's see the program,
----------------------

package ashokit.in;

public class Car {

	// we have declared a variable

	private IEngine eng;
public void drive() {

		int start = eng.start();

		if (start >= 1) {

			System.out.println("Journey started");
		} else {

			System.out.println("Engine is in trouble ");
		}
	}
}


########## We can access private variables outside of the class by using " reflection api " like below -->  

Main.java
=========

package ashokit.in;

import java.lang.reflect.Field;

public class Main {

	public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

		
		//Class.forName is used to load the class into jvm
		Class<?> clz = Class.forName("ashokit.in.Car");
		
		
		//Here we use reflection api
		Field engField = clz.getDeclaredField("eng");
		engField.setAccessible(true);
	   
		//By using --newInstance();--we create an object like "new" keyword
		Object object = clz.newInstance();
		
		Car carobj = (Car) object;
		//Here I am injecting the value to the variable 
		engField.set(carobj, new DieselEngine());
		carobj.drive();
		 

	}
}


NOTE: This is not recommended because this is violating the OOPS principles .........



















